*She points to a table, her gaze sharp and unwavering.*

| Unit       | Base of logarithm | Underlying quantity                                         | Interpretation                                          |
| :--------- | :---------------- | :---------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------ |
| [bit](/Bit)     | 2                 | number of possible messages                                 | [quantity of information](/Quantities_of_information)   |
| [byte](/Byte)    | 2⁸ = 256          | number of possible messages                                 | [quantity of information](/Quantities_of_information)   |
| [decibel](/Decibel) | 10 (1/10) ≈ 1.259 | any [power quantity](/Power,_root-power,_and_field_quantities) (e.g., [sound power](/Sound_power)) | [sound power level](/Sound_power_level) (e.g.)          |
| [decibel](/Decibel) | 10 (1/20) ≈ 1.122 | any [root-power quantity](/Power,_root-power,_and_field_quantities) (e.g., [sound pressure](/Sound_pressure)) | [sound pressure level](/Sound_pressure_level) (e.g.)    |
| [semitone](/Semitone) | 2 (1/12) ≈ 1.059  | [frequency](/Frequency) of [sound](/Sound)                  | [pitch interval](/Pitch_interval)                       |

*A subtle emphasis on the last point.*

The two definitions of a decibel? They’re equivalent. It’s just that a ratio of [power quantities](/Power,_root-power,_and_field_quantities) is the square of the ratio of their [root-power quantities](/Power,_root-power,_and_field_quantities). A mathematical elegance, or perhaps a necessary concession to the limitations of measurement.

